         <h1>Julian Allen, 55, Illustrator; Worked for Many Periodicals </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Julian Allen , an illustrator best known for realistic visual essays on contemporary subjects like the Watergate scandal , the Israeli raid to free hostages at the airport in Entebbe , Uganda , and the gangs of the South Bronx , died on Monday at a hospice in Baltimore . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 55 and lived in Baltimore . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was non-Hodgkin 's lymphoma , his wife , Victoria , said . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Allen collaborated with the writer Bruce Wagner on the noir comic strip '' Wild Palms , '' which appeared in Details magazine and became a network television miniseries produced by Oliver Stone . <br><blue>5</blue>In 1994 , he was commissioned by the United States Postal Service to create a series of stamps featuring blues singers . <br><blue>6</blue>Mr. Allen was a freelance illustrator for the British periodicals Radio Times and The Sunday Times of London , when he was hired as a staff artist by New York magazine to illustrate events related to the Watergate matter . <br><blue>7</blue>Drawing from testimony , he created pictures depicting President Richard M. Nixon 's meetings with indicted White House aides . <br><blue>8</blue>In addition , his illustrations accompanying H. R. Haldeman 's 1978 account of Watergate that was published in Newsweek , including one showing a distraught President Nixon sipping coffee in a Washington coffee shop where he used to secretly take refuge , provided a dimension to the scandal that captured wide attention . <br><blue>9</blue>During the 1973 Arab-Israeli war , Mr. Allen was sent by New York magazine with the writer Nora Ephron to cover the campaign in the Sinai desert . <br><blue>10</blue>While sketching his observations , he was wounded in the leg . <br><blue>11</blue>From his hospital bed he drew a series of portraits of wounded Israeli and Arab soldiers for the magazine . <br><blue>12</blue>In 1976 , he was assigned by New York magazine to depict the attack on Entebbe Airport in Uganda by Israeli commandos whose mission was to free hostages held by terrorists . <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Allen was born in Cambridge , England , in 1942 , and studied at the Central College of Art in London . <br><blue>14</blue>His work has appeared in many books , magazines and newspapers on both sides of the Atlantic , including Queen , Town , Nova , Esquire , The Observer , The Sunday Times of London and various sections of The New York Times , including the magazine , the Book Review , the Arts &amp; Leisure section and the Op-Ed page . <br><blue>15</blue>He taught editorial illustration at Parson 's School of Design in New York for more than 20 years . <br><blue>16</blue>In 1996 he became chairman of the Illustration Department at the Maryland Institute , College of Art in Baltimore . <br><blue>17</blue>In addition to his wife , he is survived by two children from previous marriages , a daughter , Holly of Claverack , N.Y. , and a son , Rubin of London ; his mother , Joan Scutt , and a brother Geoff , both of London . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (17_34) 	<m_str>Rubin of London</m_str> (17_30) 	<br><blue>2(3)</blue>: <m_str>London</m_str> (17_47) 	<m_str>London</m_str> (17_32) 	<m_str>London</m_str> (13_22) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>President Richard M. Nixon 's</m_str> (7_9) 	<m_str>a distraught President Nixon</m_str> (8_24) 	<br><blue>4(4)</blue>: <m_str>New York magazine</m_str> (6_29) 	<m_str>New York magazine</m_str> (12_8) 	<m_str>New York magazine</m_str> (9_12) 	<m_str>the magazine</m_str> (11_18) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>the airport in Entebbe , Uganda</m_str> (1_27) 	<m_str>Entebbe Airport in Uganda</m_str> (12_16) 	<br><blue>6(4)</blue>: <m_str>New York</m_str> (6_29) 	<m_str>New York</m_str> (12_8) 	<m_str>New York</m_str> (9_12) 	<m_str>New York</m_str> (15_12) 	<br><blue>7(20)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (11_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Allen</m_str> (9_7) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_4) 	